  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-001",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int 2x\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^5 dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6 + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{6} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{12} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{2x^2\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{6} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Let $u = x^2 + 1$, so $du = 2x\\,dx$, which is exactly the rest of the integrand. The integral becomes $\\int u^5\\,du = \\frac{u^6}{6} + C = \\frac{\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{6} + C$. Differentiating with the chain rule returns $\\frac{6\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^5}{6}\\cdot 2x = 2x\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^5$, so the answer checks. The option $\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6 + C$ forgets to divide by the new exponent $6$, $\\frac{\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{12} + C$ divides by $6$ and again by the $2$ that $du$ already consumed, and the option $\\frac{2x^2\\left(x^2 + 1\\right)^6}{6} + C$ drags a stray $2x$ outside. The trap is double-counting the $2x$: once $du = 2x\\,dx$ absorbs it, no extra factor remains.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-002",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int x e^{x}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$x e^{x} + e^{x} + C$",
        "$x e^{x} - e^{x} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{x^2}{2}e^{x} + C$",
        "$x e^{x} - \\dfrac{x^2}{2}e^{x} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Integrate by parts with $u = x$ and $dv = e^{x}\\,dx$, so $du = dx$ and $v = e^{x}$. Then $\\int x e^{x}\\,dx = uv - \\int v\\,du = x e^{x} - \\int e^{x}\\,dx = x e^{x} - e^{x} + C$. Differentiating gives $e^{x} + x e^{x} - e^{x} = x e^{x}$, which matches. The option $x e^{x} + e^{x} + C$ uses the wrong sign, writing $uv + \\int v\\,du$ instead of minus, $\\frac{x^2}{2}e^{x} + C$ integrates the product as if each factor integrated separately, and the option $x e^{x} - \\frac{x^2}{2}e^{x} + C$ swaps $u$ and $dv$ so that $dv = x\\,dx$ pulls a quadratic out. The trap is the parts sign: the formula is $uv - \\int v\\,du$, and the minus is not optional.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-003",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{1}{(x - 1)(x + 3)}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{1}{4}\\ln\\left|\\dfrac{x + 3}{x - 1}\\right| + C$",
        "$\\ln\\left|(x - 1)(x + 3)\\right| + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{2}\\ln\\left|\\dfrac{x - 1}{x + 3}\\right| + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{4}\\ln\\left|\\dfrac{x - 1}{x + 3}\\right| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Write $\\frac{1}{(x - 1)(x + 3)} = \\frac{A}{x - 1} + \\frac{B}{x + 3}$. Cover-up at $x = 1$ gives $A = \\frac{1}{1 + 3} = \\frac{1}{4}$, and at $x = -3$ gives $B = \\frac{1}{-3 - 1} = -\\frac{1}{4}$. Integrating, $\\frac{1}{4}\\ln|x - 1| - \\frac{1}{4}\\ln|x + 3| = \\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\left|\\frac{x - 1}{x + 3}\\right| + C$, whose derivative is $\\frac{1}{4}\\left(\\frac{1}{x-1} - \\frac{1}{x+3}\\right) = \\frac{1}{(x-1)(x+3)}$. The option $\\frac{1}{4}\\ln\\left|\\frac{x+3}{x-1}\\right|$ swaps the cover-up values, attaching $+\\frac{1}{4}$ to $x + 3$ and $-\\frac{1}{4}$ to $x - 1$; the log-of-product option integrates as if the denominator were a single linear factor; and the $\\frac{1}{2}$ option uses the wrong constant. The trap is assigning each cover-up residue to its own factor: $A$ belongs over $x - 1$, $B$ over $x + 3$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-004",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\sin^2 x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{x}{2} - \\dfrac{\\sin 2x}{4} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{x}{2} + \\dfrac{\\sin 2x}{4} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{x}{2} - \\dfrac{\\sin 2x}{2} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "An even power of sine needs the half-angle identity $\\sin^2 x = \\frac{1 - \\cos 2x}{2}$. Integrating, $\\int \\frac{1 - \\cos 2x}{2}\\,dx = \\frac{x}{2} - \\frac{\\sin 2x}{4} + C$. Differentiating returns $\\frac{1}{2} - \\frac{2\\cos 2x}{4} = \\frac{1 - \\cos 2x}{2} = \\sin^2 x$, so the answer checks. The option $\\frac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$ applies the reverse power rule to $\\sin x$ with no $\\cos x$ factor present to be a derivative; the $+\\frac{\\sin 2x}{4}$ option uses the identity for $\\cos^2 x$ instead of $\\sin^2 x$, flipping the sign; and the $-\\frac{\\sin 2x}{2}$ option forgets that integrating $\\cos 2x$ divides by $2$. The trap is reaching for the power rule on an even power of sine: with no odd factor to peel off, the half-angle identity is the only way in.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-005",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\cos(3x)\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$3\\sin(3x) + C$",
        "$\\sin(3x) + C$",
        "$-\\dfrac{1}{3}\\sin(3x) + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{3}\\sin(3x) + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Let $u = 3x$, so $du = 3\\,dx$ and $dx = \\frac{1}{3}\\,du$. Then $\\int \\cos(3x)\\,dx = \\frac{1}{3}\\int \\cos u\\,du = \\frac{1}{3}\\sin(3x) + C$. Differentiating gives $\\frac{1}{3}\\cdot 3\\cos(3x) = \\cos(3x)$, confirming the answer. The option $3\\sin(3x) + C$ multiplies by $3$ instead of dividing, $\\sin(3x) + C$ ignores the inner derivative entirely, and $-\\frac{1}{3}\\sin(3x) + C$ imports a minus sign that belongs to integrating cosine of nothing. The trap is the constant factor from a linear substitution: integrating $\\cos(kx)$ divides by $k$, it does not multiply.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-006",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\ln x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{1}{x} + C$",
        "$x\\ln x - x + C$",
        "$x\\ln x + x + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\left(\\ln x\\right)^2}{2} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "There is no product in sight, so take $u = \\ln x$ and $dv = dx$, giving $du = \\frac{1}{x}\\,dx$ and $v = x$. Then $\\int \\ln x\\,dx = x\\ln x - \\int x\\cdot\\frac{1}{x}\\,dx = x\\ln x - \\int 1\\,dx = x\\ln x - x + C$. Differentiating gives $\\ln x + x\\cdot\\frac{1}{x} - 1 = \\ln x$, so it checks. The option $\\frac{1}{x} + C$ differentiates $\\ln x$ rather than integrating it, $x\\ln x + x + C$ flips the parts sign to $uv + \\int v\\,du$, and $\\frac{(\\ln x)^2}{2} + C$ treats $\\ln x$ as if $\\frac{1}{x}\\,dx$ were already attached as $du$. The trap is forgetting the standard parts setup for $\\ln x$: with $dv = dx$, the leftover integral collapses to $\\int 1\\,dx$, and the parts minus sign stays.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-007",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{5x - 3}{x^2 - 2x - 3}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$2\\ln|x - 3| + 3\\ln|x + 1| + C$",
        "$\\ln\\left|x^2 - 2x - 3\\right| + C$",
        "$3\\ln|x + 1| + 2\\ln|x - 3| + C$",
        "$3\\ln|x - 3| + 2\\ln|x + 1| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Factor the denominator as $(x - 3)(x + 1)$ and write $\\frac{5x - 3}{(x - 3)(x + 1)} = \\frac{A}{x - 3} + \\frac{B}{x + 1}$. Cover-up at $x = 3$ gives $A = \\frac{15 - 3}{3 + 1} = 3$, and at $x = -1$ gives $B = \\frac{-5 - 3}{-1 - 3} = 2$. Integrating yields $3\\ln|x - 3| + 2\\ln|x + 1| + C$, whose derivative is $\\frac{3}{x-3} + \\frac{2}{x+1} = \\frac{5x - 3}{x^2 - 2x - 3}$. The option $2\\ln|x - 3| + 3\\ln|x + 1|$ swaps the two cover-up values; the option $3\\ln|x + 1| + 2\\ln|x - 3|$ attaches each residue to the wrong factor; and the single-log option pretends the numerator is the derivative of the denominator, which it is not. The trap is matching residues to factors: $A = 3$ sits over $x - 3$ because $x = 3$ is the root that kills $x - 3$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-008",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\sin^3 x \\cos x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{\\sin^4 x \\cos^2 x}{8} + C$",
        "$-\\dfrac{\\cos^4 x}{4} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\sin^4 x}{4} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "The factor $\\cos x\\,dx$ is the derivative of $\\sin x$, so let $u = \\sin x$, $du = \\cos x\\,dx$. The integral becomes $\\int u^3\\,du = \\frac{u^4}{4} + C = \\frac{\\sin^4 x}{4} + C$. Differentiating gives $\\frac{4\\sin^3 x}{4}\\cos x = \\sin^3 x\\cos x$, confirming the answer. The option $\\frac{\\sin^4 x\\cos^2 x}{8} + C$ integrates each factor on its own, $-\\frac{\\cos^4 x}{4} + C$ substitutes $u = \\cos x$ but then there is no spare $\\sin x$ to supply $du$, and $\\frac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$ ignores the $\\cos x$ factor altogether. The trap is choosing the wrong $u$ for an odd power: keep the lone $\\cos x$ as $du$ and let $u = \\sin x$.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-009",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int x\\sqrt{x^2 + 4}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{2}{3}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{2}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{x^2}{2}\\cdot\\dfrac{2}{3}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{3}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Let $u = x^2 + 4$, so $du = 2x\\,dx$ and $x\\,dx = \\frac{1}{2}\\,du$. Then $\\int x\\sqrt{x^2 + 4}\\,dx = \\frac{1}{2}\\int u^{1/2}\\,du = \\frac{1}{2}\\cdot\\frac{2}{3}u^{3/2} + C = \\frac{1}{3}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2} + C$. Differentiating gives $\\frac{1}{3}\\cdot\\frac{3}{2}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{1/2}\\cdot 2x = x\\sqrt{x^2 + 4}$, which matches. The option $\\frac{2}{3}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2}$ forgets the $\\frac{1}{2}$ from solving $x\\,dx = \\frac{1}{2}\\,du$; $\\frac{1}{2}\\left(x^2 + 4\\right)^{3/2}$ keeps the $\\frac{1}{2}$ but drops the $\\frac{2}{3}$ from the power rule; and the option that keeps an explicit $\\frac{x^2}{2}$ factor outside leaves the variable undigested. The trap is the missing constant factor: the lone $x$ supplies only half of $du$, so a $\\frac{1}{2}$ must come along.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-010",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\arctan x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$x\\arctan x - \\dfrac{1}{2}\\ln\\left(1 + x^2\\right) + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{1}{1 + x^2} + C$",
        "$x\\arctan x + \\dfrac{1}{2}\\ln\\left(1 + x^2\\right) + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\left(\\arctan x\\right)^2}{2} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "Take $u = \\arctan x$ and $dv = dx$, so $du = \\frac{1}{1 + x^2}\\,dx$ and $v = x$. Then $\\int \\arctan x\\,dx = x\\arctan x - \\int \\frac{x}{1 + x^2}\\,dx$. The leftover integral is $\\frac{1}{2}\\ln\\left(1 + x^2\\right)$ by the substitution $w = 1 + x^2$, so the answer is $x\\arctan x - \\frac{1}{2}\\ln\\left(1 + x^2\\right) + C$. Differentiating gives $\\arctan x + \\frac{x}{1 + x^2} - \\frac{x}{1 + x^2} = \\arctan x$. The option $\\frac{1}{1 + x^2} + C$ differentiates instead of integrating, the $+\\frac{1}{2}\\ln$ option flips the parts sign to plus, and $\\frac{(\\arctan x)^2}{2} + C$ treats the integrand as if its own derivative were attached. The trap is the parts sign carried onto the leftover log term: it stays negative.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-011",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{3x + 6}{x^2 + 2x - 8}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\ln|x + 4| + 2\\ln|x - 2| + C$",
        "$2\\ln|x + 4| + \\ln|x - 2| + C$",
        "$2\\ln|x - 2| - \\ln|x + 4| + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{3}{2}\\ln\\left|x^2 + 2x - 8\\right| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "Factor the denominator as $(x + 4)(x - 2)$ and set $\\frac{3x + 6}{(x + 4)(x - 2)} = \\frac{A}{x + 4} + \\frac{B}{x - 2}$. Cover-up at $x = -4$ gives $A = \\frac{3(-4) + 6}{-4 - 2} = \\frac{-6}{-6} = 1$, and at $x = 2$ gives $B = \\frac{3(2) + 6}{2 + 4} = \\frac{12}{6} = 2$. Integrating yields $\\ln|x + 4| + 2\\ln|x - 2| + C$, whose derivative is $\\frac{1}{x + 4} + \\frac{2}{x - 2} = \\frac{3x + 6}{x^2 + 2x - 8}$, so the answer checks. The option $2\\ln|x + 4| + \\ln|x - 2|$ swaps the two cover-up values between the factors, the option $2\\ln|x - 2| - \\ln|x + 4|$ swaps them and flips a sign, and the single-log option treats the numerator as the derivative of the denominator, which it is not. The trap is swapping the partial-fraction constants: $A = 1$ comes from the root $x = -4$ and belongs over $x + 4$, while $B = 2$ comes from $x = 2$ and belongs over $x - 2$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-012",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\tan x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\sec^2 x + C$",
        "$-\\ln|\\cos x| + C$",
        "$\\ln|\\cos x| + C$",
        "$\\ln|\\sin x| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Write $\\tan x = \\frac{\\sin x}{\\cos x}$ and let $u = \\cos x$, so $du = -\\sin x\\,dx$. Then $\\int \\tan x\\,dx = -\\int \\frac{du}{u} = -\\ln|u| + C = -\\ln|\\cos x| + C$, which is also written $\\ln|\\sec x| + C$. Differentiating $-\\ln|\\cos x|$ gives $-\\frac{-\\sin x}{\\cos x} = \\tan x$, confirming the answer. The option $\\sec^2 x + C$ is the derivative of $\\tan x$, not an antiderivative; $\\ln|\\cos x| + C$ drops the minus sign produced by $du = -\\sin x\\,dx$; and $\\ln|\\sin x| + C$ substitutes in the numerator by mistake, which would integrate $\\cot x$. The trap is the sign from $du$: because $\\frac{d}{dx}\\cos x = -\\sin x$, the logarithm picks up a leading minus.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-013",
      "stem": "Evaluate the definite integral $\\displaystyle\\int_{0}^{1} 2x\\,e^{x^2}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$e^2 - 1$",
        "$e - 1$",
        "$\\dfrac{e - 1}{2}$",
        "$e$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Let $u = x^2$, so $du = 2x\\,dx$, and change the limits: $x = 0$ gives $u = 0$, $x = 1$ gives $u = 1$. The integral becomes $\\int_{0}^{1} e^{u}\\,du = e^{1} - e^{0} = e - 1$. With converted limits no back-substitution is needed. The option $e^2 - 1$ keeps the original $x$-limits and writes $e^{x^2}$ evaluated as $e^{1}$ but mislabels the upper value, $\\frac{e - 1}{2}$ tacks on a stray $\\frac{1}{2}$ even though $2x\\,dx$ matches $du$ exactly, and $e$ never subtracts the lower-limit value $e^{0} = 1$. The trap is the limits of a definite substitution: once $u$ runs from $0$ to $1$, evaluate in $u$ and do not reintroduce $x$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-014",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int x^2 e^{x}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$x^2 e^{x} + 2x e^{x} + 2e^{x} + C$",
        "$x^2 e^{x} - 2x e^{x} + 2e^{x} + C$",
        "$x^2 e^{x} - 2x e^{x} - 2e^{x} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{x^3}{3}e^{x} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Apply parts twice. First $u = x^2$, $dv = e^{x}\\,dx$ gives $x^2 e^{x} - \\int 2x e^{x}\\,dx$. Parts again on $\\int 2x e^{x}\\,dx$ gives $2x e^{x} - 2e^{x}$, so the full antiderivative is $x^2 e^{x} - 2x e^{x} + 2e^{x} + C$. Differentiating returns $x^2 e^{x}$ after the middle terms cancel in pairs. The option with all plus signs flips the parts sign on the first round; the option ending in $-2e^{x}$ drops a sign in the second application of parts; and $\\frac{x^3}{3}e^{x} + C$ integrates the power and the exponential separately. The trap in repeated parts is sign bookkeeping: each application contributes its own minus, so the signs alternate.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-015",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{1}{x^2(x + 1)}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\ln|x| - \\dfrac{1}{x} - \\ln|x + 1| + C$",
        "$-\\dfrac{1}{x} + \\ln|x + 1| + C$",
        "$-\\ln|x| - \\dfrac{1}{x} + \\ln|x + 1| + C$",
        "$\\ln\\left|x^2(x + 1)\\right| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "A repeated linear factor needs both powers, so write $\\frac{1}{x^2(x + 1)} = \\frac{A}{x} + \\frac{B}{x^2} + \\frac{D}{x + 1}$. Clearing denominators gives $1 = Ax(x + 1) + B(x + 1) + Dx^2$. Setting $x = 0$ gives $B = 1$, setting $x = -1$ gives $D = 1$, and matching the $x^2$ coefficients gives $A + D = 0$, so $A = -1$. Integrating $-\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{x^2} + \\frac{1}{x + 1}$ gives $-\\ln|x| - \\frac{1}{x} + \\ln|x + 1| + C$, whose derivative is $-\\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{x^2} + \\frac{1}{x + 1} = \\frac{1}{x^2(x + 1)}$. The option $-\\frac{1}{x} + \\ln|x + 1| + C$ omits the $\\frac{A}{x}$ term that the repeated factor still requires, the option $\\ln|x| - \\frac{1}{x} - \\ln|x + 1| + C$ flips the signs of both logarithms, and the single-log option ignores the repeated power entirely. The trap is dropping a term: a squared factor $x^2$ contributes both $\\frac{A}{x}$ and $\\frac{B}{x^2}$, not just one.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-016",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\cos^3 x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{\\cos^4 x}{4} + C$",
        "$\\sin x - \\dfrac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$",
        "$\\sin x + \\dfrac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "Peel off one cosine and convert the rest: $\\cos^3 x = \\cos x\\left(1 - \\sin^2 x\\right)$. With $u = \\sin x$, $du = \\cos x\\,dx$, the integral is $\\int \\left(1 - u^2\\right)du = u - \\frac{u^3}{3} + C = \\sin x - \\frac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$. Differentiating gives $\\cos x - \\sin^2 x\\cos x = \\cos x\\left(1 - \\sin^2 x\\right) = \\cos^3 x$. The option $\\frac{\\cos^4 x}{4} + C$ applies the power rule to $\\cos x$ with no spare $-\\sin x$ to be its $du$; the $+\\frac{\\sin^3 x}{3}$ option keeps the wrong sign on the converted term; and $\\frac{\\sin^3 x}{3} + C$ forgets the leading $\\sin x$ from the $1$ in the identity. The trap is splitting the odd power on the wrong factor: save one cosine for $du$ and rewrite the even number that remain using $\\cos^2 x = 1 - \\sin^2 x$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-017",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\arcsin\\left(\\dfrac{x}{3}\\right) + C$",
        "$3\\arcsin\\left(\\dfrac{x}{3}\\right) + C$",
        "$\\arcsin(3x) + C$",
        "$\\ln\\left|\\sqrt{9 - x^2}\\right| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "For $\\sqrt{a^2 - x^2}$ with $a = 3$, substitute $x = 3\\sin\\theta$, so $dx = 3\\cos\\theta\\,d\\theta$ and $\\sqrt{9 - x^2} = 3\\cos\\theta$. The integral becomes $\\int \\frac{3\\cos\\theta}{3\\cos\\theta}\\,d\\theta = \\int 1\\,d\\theta = \\theta + C = \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) + C$. Differentiating $\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right)$ gives $\\frac{1/3}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2/9}} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}$, which matches. The option $3\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right)$ keeps an extra factor of $3$ that the $3\\cos\\theta$ in the numerator already cancelled, $\\arcsin(3x)$ uses the wrong triangle ratio $\\frac{x}{1/3}$ instead of $\\frac{x}{3}$, and the log option mistakes this for a $\\frac{1}{u}$ form. The trap is the triangle side: with $x = a\\sin\\theta$ the argument of arcsine is $\\frac{x}{a}$, here $\\frac{x}{3}$, not $3x$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-018",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{1}{x^2 + 16}\\,dx$.",
