      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "For $\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}$ substitute $x = \\sec\\theta$, so $dx = \\sec\\theta\\tan\\theta\\,d\\theta$ and $\\sqrt{x^2 - 1} = \\tan\\theta$. The integral becomes $\\int \\frac{\\sec\\theta\\tan\\theta}{\\sec^2\\theta\\,\\tan\\theta}\\,d\\theta = \\int \\cos\\theta\\,d\\theta = \\sin\\theta + C$. From the reference triangle, $\\sin\\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}{x}$, so the integral is $\\frac{\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}{x} + C$. Differentiating $\\frac{\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}{x}$ gives $\\frac{1}{x^2\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}$ after simplification. The option $\\sqrt{x^2 - 1} + C$ reads the hypotenuse leg as $\\tan\\theta$ rather than $\\sin\\theta$; $\\arccos\\left(\\frac{1}{x}\\right) + C$ matches $\\theta$ itself instead of $\\sin\\theta$; and the negative option reverses the sign of $\\sin\\theta$. The trap is reading the wrong side of the triangle when converting $\\theta$ back to $x$: here the answer is $\\sin\\theta = \\frac{\\text{opposite}}{\\text{hypotenuse}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}{x}$.",
