      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "Let $u = \\ln x$, so $du = \\frac{1}{x}\\,dx$, which is the rest of the integrand. The integral becomes $\\int u\\,du = \\frac{u^2}{2} + C = \\frac{(\\ln x)^2}{2} + C$. Differentiating gives $\\frac{2\\ln x}{2}\\cdot\\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{\\ln x}{x}$, which matches. The option $(\\ln x)^2 + C$ forgets to divide by the new exponent $2$, $\\ln|\\ln x| + C$ treats the integrand as $\\frac{u'}{u}$ when in fact $u = \\ln x$ and $du = \\frac{1}{x}\\,dx$ make it $\\int u\\,du$, and $\\frac{1}{2x^2}\\ln x + C$ tries to integrate the $\\frac{1}{x}$ separately. The trap is identifying $du$: since $\\frac{1}{x}\\,dx$ is exactly $du$ for $u = \\ln x$, the integral is a plain power of $u$, not a logarithm.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-022",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int e^{x}\\sin x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$e^{x}\\left(\\sin x - \\cos x\\right) + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{e^{x}\\left(\\sin x + \\cos x\\right)}{2} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{e^{x}\\left(\\sin x - \\cos x\\right)}{2} + C$",
        "$e^{x}\\cos x + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "Call the integral $I$ and apply parts twice. With $u = \\sin x$, $dv = e^{x}\\,dx$: $I = e^{x}\\sin x - \\int e^{x}\\cos x\\,dx$. Parts again on the remaining integral gives $\\int e^{x}\\cos x\\,dx = e^{x}\\cos x + \\int e^{x}\\sin x\\,dx = e^{x}\\cos x + I$. Substituting, $I = e^{x}\\sin x - e^{x}\\cos x - I$, so $2I = e^{x}(\\sin x - \\cos x)$ and $I = \\frac{e^{x}(\\sin x - \\cos x)}{2} + C$. Differentiating confirms it returns $e^{x}\\sin x$. The option without the $\\frac{1}{2}$ forgets to divide after solving $2I = \\cdots$; the $+\\cos x$ option mismanages a sign in the second parts step; and $e^{x}\\cos x + C$ stops after one application. The trap is the recursive parts step: when the original integral reappears, solve for it algebraically and divide by $2$.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-023",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{x + 4}{x(x - 2)}\\,dx$.",
