        "$2\\arcsin\\left(\\dfrac{x}{2}\\right) - \\dfrac{x\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2} + C$",
        "$\\arcsin\\left(\\dfrac{x}{2}\\right) + \\dfrac{x\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 1,
      "explanation": "With $a = 2$, set $x = 2\\sin\\theta$, so $dx = 2\\cos\\theta\\,d\\theta$ and $\\sqrt{4 - x^2} = 2\\cos\\theta$. The integral becomes $\\int 4\\cos^2\\theta\\,d\\theta = 2\\int (1 + \\cos 2\\theta)\\,d\\theta = 2\\theta + \\sin 2\\theta + C$. Since $\\sin 2\\theta = 2\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta = 2\\cdot\\frac{x}{2}\\cdot\\frac{\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2} = \\frac{x\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2}$, the answer is $2\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right) + \\frac{x\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2} + C$. Differentiating recovers $\\sqrt{4 - x^2}$. The option $\\frac{(4 - x^2)^{3/2}}{3} + C$ pretends a stray $x$ factor is present to make a plain substitution work; the minus-sign option mishandles the double-angle term; and the option $\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right) + \\frac{x\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2} + C$ drops the leading $2$ from $2\\theta$. The trap is converting $\\sin 2\\theta$ back through the reference triangle: read both legs, $\\sin\\theta = \\frac{x}{2}$ and $\\cos\\theta = \\frac{\\sqrt{4 - x^2}}{2}$.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
