      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "Set $x = 3\\sin\\theta$, so $dx = 3\\cos\\theta\\,d\\theta$, $x^2 = 9\\sin^2\\theta$, and $\\sqrt{9 - x^2} = 3\\cos\\theta$. The integral becomes $\\int \\frac{9\\sin^2\\theta}{3\\cos\\theta}\\cdot 3\\cos\\theta\\,d\\theta = 9\\int \\sin^2\\theta\\,d\\theta = \\frac{9}{2}\\left(\\theta - \\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta\\right) + C$. Converting back with $\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta = \\frac{x}{3}\\cdot\\frac{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}{3} = \\frac{x\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}{9}$ gives $\\frac{9}{2}\\arcsin\\left(\\frac{x}{3}\\right) - \\frac{x\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}{2} + C$, whose derivative simplifies to $\\frac{x^2}{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}$. The $+$ option flips the sign on the second term; $-\\sqrt{9 - x^2} + C$ is the antiderivative of $\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}$, not $\\frac{x^2}{\\sqrt{9 - x^2}}$; and the option $\\frac{x^3}{3\\sqrt{9 - x^2}} + C$ integrates numerator and denominator separately. The trap is the wrong triangle side again: $\\sin\\theta\\cos\\theta$ must be rebuilt from both legs of the $x = 3\\sin\\theta$ triangle.",
