      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "The numerator $x$ is, up to the constant $\\frac{1}{2}$, the derivative of the denominator $x^2 + 1$, so $u = x^2 + 1$ with $du = 2x\\,dx$ turns the integral into $\\frac{1}{2}\\int \\frac{du}{u} = \\frac{1}{2}\\ln(x^2 + 1) + C$. Parts would work but needs the antiderivative of $\\frac{1}{x^2 + 1}$, which is arctangent, making it a detour; partial fractions fails because $x^2 + 1$ is irreducible over the reals, so it does not split into linear factors; and trigonometric substitution buries a one-line problem in trig identities. The trap is reaching for a heavy method when the numerator already signals a simple substitution: if the top is the derivative of the bottom, substitute.",
      "difficulty": "warmup",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-028",
      "stem": "Which technique evaluates $\\displaystyle\\int x\\cos x\\,dx$ most directly?",
      "options": [
        "Substitution with $u = \\cos x$.",
