        "$3\\ln|x - 1| - 4\\ln|x - 1| + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 0,
      "explanation": "A repeated linear factor needs $\\frac{3x + 1}{(x - 1)^2} = \\frac{A}{x - 1} + \\frac{B}{(x - 1)^2}$. Clearing denominators, $3x + 1 = A(x - 1) + B$. At $x = 1$, $B = 4$; matching the $x$ coefficient, $A = 3$. Integrating $\\frac{3}{x - 1} + \\frac{4}{(x - 1)^2}$ gives $3\\ln|x - 1| - \\frac{4}{x - 1} + C$. Differentiating returns $\\frac{3}{x - 1} + \\frac{4}{(x - 1)^2} = \\frac{3x + 1}{(x - 1)^2}$. The option $+\\frac{4}{x - 1}$ forgets that $\\int (x - 1)^{-2}\\,dx = -(x - 1)^{-1}$ carries a minus; the option $\\frac{3x + 1}{-(x - 1)}$ integrates the whole fraction as one reciprocal; and the option $3\\ln|x - 1| - 4\\ln|x - 1|$ treats $\\frac{B}{(x - 1)^2}$ as another logarithm instead of a power. The trap is integrating the repeated-factor term as a log: $\\frac{1}{(x - 1)^2}$ is a power, so it integrates to $-\\frac{1}{x - 1}$, not a logarithm.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Schaum's Outline of Calculus"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-032",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\sec^4 x\\,dx$.",
      "options": [
        "$\\dfrac{\\sec^5 x}{5} + C$",
        "$\\tan x - \\dfrac{\\tan^3 x}{3} + C$",
        "$\\dfrac{\\tan^3 x}{3} + C$",
        "$\\tan x + \\dfrac{\\tan^3 x}{3} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 3,
      "explanation": "Save one $\\sec^2 x$ for $du$ and convert the other using $\\sec^2 x = 1 + \\tan^2 x$: $\\int \\sec^4 x\\,dx = \\int (1 + \\tan^2 x)\\sec^2 x\\,dx$. With $u = \\tan x$, $du = \\sec^2 x\\,dx$, this is $\\int (1 + u^2)\\,du = u + \\frac{u^3}{3} + C = \\tan x + \\frac{\\tan^3 x}{3} + C$. Differentiating gives $\\sec^2 x + \\tan^2 x\\sec^2 x = (1 + \\tan^2 x)\\sec^2 x = \\sec^4 x$. The option $\\frac{\\sec^5 x}{5} + C$ applies the power rule to $\\sec x$ with no $\\sec x\\tan x$ factor to be its $du$; the $-\\frac{\\tan^3 x}{3}$ option flips the sign of the converted term; and $\\frac{\\tan^3 x}{3} + C$ drops the $\\tan x$ from the $1$ in the identity. The trap is splitting the even power of secant on the wrong factor: keep one $\\sec^2 x$ as $du$ and rewrite the rest with $\\sec^2 x = 1 + \\tan^2 x$.",
      "difficulty": "core",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-033",
      "stem": "Evaluate $\\displaystyle\\int \\tan^3 x \\sec^3 x\\,dx$.",
