        "$\\dfrac{\\sec^6 x}{6} + C$"
      ],
      "answer": 2,
      "explanation": "With an odd power of tangent, peel off one $\\sec x\\tan x$ for $du$ and convert the remaining even tangents: $\\tan^3 x\\sec^3 x = \\tan^2 x\\sec^2 x\\cdot(\\sec x\\tan x) = (\\sec^2 x - 1)\\sec^2 x\\,(\\sec x\\tan x)$. Let $u = \\sec x$, $du = \\sec x\\tan x\\,dx$, giving $\\int (u^2 - 1)u^2\\,du = \\int (u^4 - u^2)\\,du = \\frac{u^5}{5} - \\frac{u^3}{3} + C = \\frac{\\sec^5 x}{5} - \\frac{\\sec^3 x}{3} + C$. Differentiating recovers $\\tan^3 x\\sec^3 x$. The $+\\frac{\\sec^3 x}{3}$ option drops the minus from $\\tan^2 x = \\sec^2 x - 1$; the product option integrates each factor separately; and $\\frac{\\sec^6 x}{6} + C$ pretends the whole integrand is $\\sec^5 x\\cdot(\\sec x\\tan x)$, miscounting the powers. The trap is splitting the sec-tan product on the wrong factor: with odd tangent, reserve $\\sec x\\tan x$ for $du$ and rewrite the even tangents as $\\sec^2 x - 1$.",
      "difficulty": "stretch",
      "source": "in the style of Stewart 8e, chapter 7"
    },
    {
      "id": "calculus-ii-integration-techniques-034",
